<TEXT>
president augusto pinochet says that 
although the constitution prevents him from running for reelection 
he will still pick the candidate he wants to succeed him and will 
not step down as army chief 
im going to tell you soon whom we must support in 
presidential balloting scheduled for dec 14 the rightwing general 
told cheering supporters on sunday in temuco 370 miles south of 
santiago 
lets stay together lets not quarrel among ourselves the 
72yearold army commander said in his speech carried by santiago 
newspapers on monday we should not yield the field to those other 
gentlemen in the opposition 
congressional elections also will be held dec 14 
the temuco speech quickly drew fire from opposition leaders who 
called pinochets remarks a threat to any future elected government 
pinochet was ending an eightday tour of southern chile during 
which he made clear that he plans to retain a key role in chile once 
he steps down from the presidency in march 1990 
the 55000men army is by far the most powerful of the armed 
services and the key to pinochets hold of power for more than 15 
years 
under a 1980 militarywritten constitution pinochet is allowed 
to remain army commander for eight years after leaving the 
presidency he must hand power over on march 11 1990 to the winner 
of the december election 
andres zaldivar vice president of the centrist christian 
democratic party said monday of pinochets remarks thats 
unacceptable pinochet should leave the army as a gesture of 
dignity 
pinochet took power in a violent 1973 coup that toppled the 
elected government of salvador allende a marxist who died in the 
takeover 
pinochet was obliged to call the elections after losing an oct 5 
referendum in which he sought voters approval to remain in power 
until 1997 
after the referendum defeat the propinochet forces split at 
least two politicians formally announced their candidacies for 
president and conservative business leaders are actively promoting 
the nomination of pinochets 39yearold finance minister hernan 
buchi 
several small groups also asked that a formula be found probably 
a constitutional amendment to allow pinochet to run he insists 
however he definitely will not be a candidate the constitution 
bars him from running 
but pinochet has made it clear that he plans to play an active 
role in the campaign and the election by telling his followers for 
whom to vote 
the opposition says it plans to seek a single presidential 
candidate leaders of a coalition of 17 opposition parties are 
scheduled to pick the nominee next month among at least four 
contenders 
patricio aylwin a former senate president is considered the 
frontrunner 
aylwin is president of the christian democrats the largest 
opposition party and was the oppositions chief spokesman during 
the campaign for the referendum 
