<TEXT>
the supreme court today voted to resolve a 
significant dispute over the freedom of information act while 
agreeing to keep the identities of the legal combatants a secret 
the justices said they will decide whether a government law 
enforcement agency must surrender to a government contractor being 
investigated for possible fraud certain documents received from 
another agency 
much of the case is cloaked in secrecy including the identity 
of the contractor and the government agencies involved presumably 
to protect the contractors reputation 
the 2nd us circuit court of appeals based in new york city 
ruled last june 23 that the soughtafter government documents must 
be released to the contractor but supreme court justice thurgood 
marshall on jan 30 blocked any such release until the high court 
considered the governments appeal 
the documents at issue are 1978 letters a government agency 
referred to in court papers as the john doe agency exchanged with 
the contractor identified as john doe corp about the contractors 
billing practices 
those letters became relevant in 1986 during a grand jury 
investigation of possible fraudulent practices by the contractor 
and they were tranferred from the john doe agency to a federal law 
enforcement agency identified in court papers as john doe 
government agency 
the contractor under investigation filed an foia lawsuit in 1987 
seeking all documents that are related in any way to the subject 
matter of the 1978 correspondence 
a federal trial judge ruled against the contractor saying 
release of the documents would jeopardize the grand jury 
investigation 
but the 2nd circuit court ruled that the foia requires surrender 
of the documents 
an exemption in the law for materials compiled for law 
enforcement purposes does not apply in this case the appeals 
court said because the letters were not originally obtained or 
generated for law enforcement purposes 
in the appeal acted on today justice department lawyers argued 
that the june ruling would seriously impair the ability of 
numerous federal agencies to conduct their law enforcement 
responsibilities and hinder an important law enforcement 
investigation 
the case is john doe agency vs john doe corp 881083 
