the supreme court today agreed to decide 
whether people who do not own property may be excluded from 
membership on a public body authorized to recommend a reorganization 
of local government in the st louis area 
the court said it will hear a challenge to the makeup of the st 
louis cityst louis county board of freeholders 
the board of freeholders was created to write a proposed charter 
for reorganizing the city and county government structure the board 
also was empowered to recommend new taxes to finance the city and 
county governments 
any proposals by the board would be submitted to the voters in a 
referendum 
board members were ppointed by the mayor of st louis the county 
executive and the governor of missouri 
state representative robert j quinn a st louis county resident 
who does not own property said his rights were violated by a state 
constitutional requirement limiting membership on the freeholder 
board to property owners 
quinn suing for himself and all others in the city and county 
who do not own property said the exclusion violated the us 
constitutions guarantee of equal protection under law 
but the missouri supreme court ruled last september that the 
federal constitutional protection does not apply because the 
freeholder board does not have general governmental powers 
the board of freeholders serves only to recommend a plan of 
reorganization to the voters of st louis city and st louis 
county the state court said it can recommend property 
taxes and sales taxes but it cannot levy and collect them in sum 
the board of freeholders has no general governmental powers 
the state court said the st louis case is not covered by past 
us supreme court rulings that struck down property ownership as a 
qualification for membership on a city school board or regional 
airport commission 
the case is quinn vs millsap 881048 
</TEXT>
