<DOCNO> AP890221-0076 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court let stand rulings that the 
public has no right to attend the socalled summary jury trials 
held in some legal disputes 
the justices without comment rejected arguments by newspapers 
in three ohio cities that trial judges should be barred from 
conducting such proceedings in secret 
the newspapers lawyers had asked the high court to rule for the 
first time that the constitution provides a public right of access 
to judicial proceedings in civil or noncriminal cases 
the court in 1980 ruled that the public has a right to attend 
criminal trials even when defendants object the justices since have 
expanded that ruling to cover jury selection and pretrial 
proceedings in criminal cases 
but the court never has ruled that such a right of access exists 
as well for civil trials and proceedings 
the appeal acted on today stems from a 1984 lawsuit by three ohio 
utilities against general electric co over the design and 
construction of the william h zimmer nuclear power plant 
the suit alleged that ge sold the utilties dayton power and 
light columbus and southern electric and cincinnati gas and 
electric co a nuclear reactor container system it knew was 
incapable of operating in a safe manner 
us district judge s arthur spiegel presided over a summary 
jury trial in the case in which lawyers for both sides presented 
summaries of their evidence 
the jurys verdict in such proceedings is advisory and 
nonbinding unless both sides agree otherwise the verdict is 
supposed to be a reliable indicator of a full trials outcome 
sparking attempts to settle so a full trial will not be necessary 
since first introduced in 1980 summary jury trials have been 
used in at least 65 federal courts in about half the states 
in the ge case the judge ruled that the summary trial would be 
closed to the public and ordered the parties lawyers and jurors 
never to reveal anything that occurred during the proceeding he 
also permanently sealed the trial transcript 
the cincinnati post the dayton daily news and the columbus 
dispatch challenged the closure but the 6th us circuit court of 
appeals ruled against them last aug 18 
the appeals court said summary jury trials are more akin to 
settlement conferences than real trials and that the public 
therefore has no right to attend or see the transcript 
there is no historically recognized of right to summary jury 
trials in that this mechanism has been in existence for less than a 
decade the appeals court said adding there is general 
agreement that historically settlement techniques are closed 
procedures 
in seeking supreme court review lawyers for the three newspapers 
argued public confidence will be lost if judges may respond to 
their expanding dockets by disposing of cases through secret 
courtroom proceedings and permanent gag orders 
this court cannot expect that public confidence so vital to an 
effective judiciary will thrive where judges conduct decisive 
courtroom proceedings behind closed doors in permanent 
courtimposed secrecy the appeal contended 
but lawyers for ge discounted what they called the appeals 
great flourishes of hyperbole and urged the justices to reject 
it 
the case is cincinnati post vs ge 88813 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

