<TEXT>
the supreme court today told federal judges to 
be tougher in secondguessing decisions by pension and welfare plans 
that deny benefits to workers 
in ruling unanimously in a case involving the firestone tire amp 
rubber co the justices said federal judges must evaluate such 
cases just as if the pension and welfare plan officials had not yet 
made any decision 
some federal courts instead have been employing a less stringent 
standard of review generally not disturbing decisions by plan 
officials unless they are found to be arbitrary or capricious 
the dispute ruled on today stemmed from firestones selling its 
plastics division in 1980 to occidental petroleum corp 
the sale affected some 500 workers at firestone plants in 
pottstown pa west caldwell nj perryville and salisbury md 
and baton rouge la 
nearly all the workers were given the opportunity to keep their 
jobs under the new ownership and most accepted 
some workers sought certain benefits from firestone including 
early retirement and severance pay that were included in the three 
firestone welfare and pension plans 
the company denied the benefits it also refused to release 
information about the benefit plans to workers who sought it on 
grounds that the workers no longer were employed by firestone and no 
longer participants in the plans 
the workers sued charging firestone with violating the federal 
employee retirement and income security act of 1974 erisa 
a federal judge threw out the suit ruling that firestone did not 
act in an arbitrary or capricious manner 
but the 3rd us circuit court of appeals reinstated the suit 
the appeals court said workers claims must be examined more closely 
in such cases writing for the supreme court today justice sandra 
day oconnor said the appeals court was right 
oconnor said the more stringent standard of judicial review 
should apply unless the plan gives its administrator or other 
officials the discretionary authority to determine eligibility for 
benefits or to construe the terms of the plan 
the justices told the 3rd circuit court to restudy the issue of 
whether the workers seeking information about the welfare and 
pension plans from firestone qualify as participants who are 
entitled under erisa to such information 
the case is firestone vs bruch 871054 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

