a convicted child molester who taught at a 
cherokee indian school for 14 years said today in videotaped 
testimony to congress that he was surprised he was able to continue 
the illicit activity for so long 
this is strictly hindsight looking back it certainly is a 
phenomenon thats hard to understand said paul wade price who is 
serving a 10year sentence in butner federal correctional 
institution in butner nc 
price pleaded guilty to one count of child molestation but in 
the tape he admitted for the first time that he had abused at least 
25 boys while he taught at the cherokee school in western north 
carolina 
under questioning by ken bellen counsel to a special 
investigative unit of the senate select committee on indian affairs 
price said no one ever tried to stop him even though he believed 
that they knew of his sexual activity with the boys 
prices testimony came as the committee began its third week of 
hearings into corruption of various kinds on the nations indian 
reservations 
a former supervisor of price testified that he was instrumental 
in having price removed from his division as a seventhgrade teacher 
at western carolina universitys campus lab school in 1971 arthur 
justice then director of the lab school had a son who was in the 
seventh grade at the school when price taught there 
justice said that his son told him of cases of sexual molestation 
by price with other seventhgraders on an overnight camping trip 
justice said he told the school superintendent about the incident 
and the superintendent waited until the end of the year to dismiss 
price 
justice said that when he found out that price was teaching at 
the bureau of indian affairs school on the cherokee reservation he 
wrote a letter to the school principal and warned him about price 
however price was not dismissed until 14 years later 
justice said that while all 50 states have child abusereporting 
laws the federal government does not 
in 1974 congress required states to enact such laws as a 
requirement for receiving federal aid 
justice who has had experience in enforcing these laws said 
even a suspicion of child abuse must be reported and a followup 
investigation must be conducted within 24 hours 
i strongly believe there needs to be some federal 
legislation he said he said there is no federal law to stop 
price from going to another indian school and committing the same 
crime again 
