<TEXT>
the supreme court in a case involving alleged 
fraud in a 20yearold business merger today limited the ability of 
people to seek additional damages after winning a lawsuit 
the 90 ruling in a case from georgia restricts the ability of 
purported fraud victims to sue a leading accounting firm 
the case arose out of the 1969 merger of cavalier bag co and 
et barwick industries inc 
the owners of cavalier bag myles guykenneth and robert 
osterneck charged in a 1975 lawsuit that the financial health of 
barwick industries was overstated 
the osternecks sued barwick officials and ernst amp whinney an 
accounting firm that had prepared the allegedly inflated financial 
statements 
after nearly 10 years of pretrial maneuvering the case went to 
trial in 1984 and the barwick company and its offficials were 
ordered to pay the osternecks more than 26 million in damages plus 
946000 in interest 
but the osternecks lost their case against ernst amp whinney 
they then appealed seeking to revive the case against the 
accounting firm that appeal was filed at the same time that the 
osternecks request for interest payments against the barwick 
officials was pending in court 
the 11th us circuit court of appeals ruled that the osternecks 
bid for damages against the accounting firm must be treated as a 
motion to amend the original judgment that the osternecks had won 
therefore the appeals court barred the osternecks from pursuing 
a separate appeal against ernst amp whinney while at the same time 
they were seeking additional interest payments against the barwick 
officials 
the supreme court today upheld the appeals court ruling 
justice anthony m kennedy writing for the court said handling 
appeals in this manner helps avoid piecemeal appellate court review 
of lower court judgments 
the case is osterneck vs ernst amp whinney 871201 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890221-0130 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a unanimous supreme court today gave lawyers 
added incentive the possibility of biggerthanbargainedfor legal 
fees to represent those who claim their civil rights were violated 
the court ruled in a louisiana case that the losing side in some 
civil rights lawsuits may be forced to pay the winning sides 
lawyers more than the lawyers originally had sought 
the normal rule in us courts is that each side pays its own 
lawyers but congress has altered that rule in about 200 
feeshifting laws and allowed the winning side to collect its 
lawyer fees from the losing side 
most notably such fee awards are available to people who 
successfully sue over civil rights violations 
arthur j blanchard who said he was assaulted without 
provocation by a st martin parish sheriffs deputy james bergeron 
was awarded 10000 in damages by a federal jury 
the presiding judge also awarded blanchard 7500 in lawyer fees 
which bergeron was ordered to pay 
but the 5th us circuit court of appeals reduced the lawyerfee 
award to 4000 after noting that blanchard and his lawyer had a 
contingencyfee agreement in which the lawyer was to get 40 percent 
of any damage award 
the appeals court said the 40 percent contingency agreement 
effectively placed a cap on any lawyerfee award that could be made 
writing for the supreme court today justice byron r white said 
no such cap exists 
if a contingent fee agreement were to govern as a strict 
limitation on the award of attorneys fees an undesirable emphasis 
might be placed on the importance of the recovery of damages in 
civil rights litigation white said 
the intention of congress he said was to encourage 
successful civil rights litigation not to create a special 
incentive to prove damages and shortchange efforts to seek effective 
injunctive or declaratory relief 
the justices told the 5th circuit court to reconsider its 
lawyerfee award ruling in blanchards case 
the case is blanchard vs bergeron 871485 
</TEXT>
