<TEXT>
here ataglance are highlights of the major 
actions taken tuesday by the supreme court 
 
pornography 
the court ruled that states may use antiracketeering laws to 
fight pornography but invoked freespeech rights to ban the states 
from seizing before trial the contents of adult bookstores 
the justices said authorities unlawfully seized the contents of a 
fort wayne ind bookstore before any materials in the store were 
judged obscene at a trial 
but by a 63 vote the justices said prosecutors still may use 
the states antiracketeering law to renew the obscenity case 
the cases are fort wayne books vs indiana 87470 and 
sappenfield vs indiana 87614 
 
religious books 
 
the court ruled that states may not give preferential treatment 
to religious ublications by exempting them from sales taxes imposed 
on other books newspapers and magazines 
by a 63 vote the justices said a nowdefunct texas statute 
violated the constitution the decision presumably will force the 
state to give sales tax refunds to nonreligious publications or 
impose the levy against religious organizations that were exempt 
the case is texas monthly vs bullock 871245 
 
summary trials 
 
the court let stand rulings that the public has no right to 
attend the socalled summary jury trials held in some legal 
disputes 
the justices without comment rejected arguments by newspapers 
in three ohio cities that trial judges should be barred from 
conducting such proceedings in secret 
the newspapers lawyers had asked the high court to rule for the 
first time that the constitution provides a public right of access 
to judicial proceedings in civil or noncriminal cases 
the case is cincinnati post vs ge 88813 
 
evangelists 
 
television evangelist jimmy swaggart failed in his bid to kill a 
90 million lawsuit by a defrocked evangelist who swaggart accused 
of adultery in 1986 
the court without comment rejected arguments that marvin 
gormans suit against swaggart and others unconstitutionally 
entangles louisiana state courts in matters of church doctrine and 
discipline 
the cases are swaggart vs adler 881080 and treeby vs gorman 
881058 
 
freedom of expression 
 
the court refused to reinstate the pandering conviction of a 
hollywood movie producer who hired actors to peform sex acts in a 
pornographic film 
the justices without comment let stand a california supreme 
court ruling that harold freemans conviction on charges of 
procuring people for purposes of prostitution violated his freedom 
of expression 
the cases are california vs freeman 881054 and applegate vs 
freeman 881050 
 
abortion 
 
the court allowed kentucky to begin enforcing a 1986 abortion law 
that included provisions for parental notification 
the justices without comment turned down an emergency request 
by prochoice advocates seeking to block the law until a federal 
appeals court rules on its constitutionality 
the case is eubanks vs wilkinson a582 
 
iran assets 
 
the court agreed to referee a dispute between the us government 
and american businesses stemming from the 1981 settlement of the 
iran hostage crisis 
the court said it will review a ruling that businesses recovering 
money from irans government do not have to pay a portion of it to 
the us government 
the case is us vs sperry corp 88952 
 
freedom of information 
 
while agreeing to keep the identities of the legal combatants a 
secret the court voted to resolve a significant dispute over the 
freedom of information act 
the justices said they will decide whether a government law 
enforcement agency must surrender to a government contractor being 
investigated for possible fraud certain documents received from 
another agency 
much of the case is cloaked in secrecy including the identity 
of the contractor and the government agencies involved presumably 
to protect the contractors reputation 
the case is john doe agency vs john doe corp 881083 
 
animal drugs 
 
the court allowed the food and drug administration to impose 
strict controls on the use of drugs by veterinarians for 
experimental treatment of some animal diseases 
the court without comment rejected arguments by an illinois 
drug distributing company that the government wrongly is interfering 
with treatment of serious animal illnesses the fda seized a large 
quantity of drugs july 9 1986 from schuyler laboratories inc in 
rushville ill 
the case is 91 kg containers vs us 88614 
</TEXT>
