<TEXT>
archbishop helder camara has turned 
80 an age at which many clergymen slip quietly into retirement but 
the human rights crusader of the 1960s and 1970s remains an 
outspoken defender of the poor at the request of pope john paul ii 
following the popes instructions i will not hang up my 
spikes the roman catholic leader said 
in accordance with church rules camara known worldwide as dom 
helder the portuguese title for the high clergy had to retire at 
75 as archbishop of recife and olinda on brazils northeast coast 
but maintained his title 
im as busy now as i ever was said the short slight 
prelate seeming even smaller in a voluminous khaki cassock adorned 
with a simple wooden cross the interview came amid a heavy schedule 
of speeches and celebrations marking his 80th birthday feb 7 
during a rightwing military regime in the worlds largest 
catholic nation from 1964 to 1985 camara denounced torture and 
human rights abuses in the face of death threats and a machinegun 
attack on his parish house 
the generals branded camara the red bishop and banned his 
name from news broadcasts his supporters nominated him for the 
nobel peace prize 
those dark days have ended but brazils chronic poverty persists 
with the collusion of powerful economic interests he says 
the forces behind these conditions are wellknown large 
multinational corporations create great problems here he said 
the multinationals have very different attitudes in their own 
countries from those they have in ours 
in 25 years as archbishop camara has condemned the 
exploitation of the third world by the industrialized nations 
he also has criticized communist powers for imposing their will on 
smaller countries but reserves his harshest words for his main 
cause these days land reform 
its a scandal he said how can 20 percent of the people 
own 80 percent of the land in a country 34 times the size of 
germany 
since 1980 more than 1000 people mostly landless peasants 
have been killed in brazil in rural property disputes 
the church supports land reform but it doesnt intend to be 
political no violence or radicalization the archbishop said 
asked if he agreed with progressive clergymen who endorse land 
invasions by the homeless camara paused this business of 
invasions is funny he said i laugh when these big landowners 
say my land was invaded where did they get it wasnt that an 
invasion 
camara said the pope also is very well informed about the 
land reform issue he thinks its now possible to end this 
scandal he said 
although the pope has emphatically told priests to stay out of 
politics and has punished radical brazilian theologists in 1980 he 
met in recife with camara then considered a nonperson by the 
military government 
on live nationwide and international tv john paul embraced dom 
helder and said this man is a friend of the poor he is my 
friend 
camara remembered that with emotion 
the pope is greater than many people think he said he is 
as great as john xxiii that pontiff who reigned from 195863 
was widely known for his warm human character 
the archbishop said he is not discouraged by the immense social 
problems in this country of 144 million where modern skyscrapers 
exist sidebyside with miserable shantytowns and where the world 
bank says the income distribution between the rich and the poor is 
the most unfair in the world 
one thing i learned from young people when the problems are 
absurd the solutions become a passion he said 
