<TEXT>
playwright vaclav havel whose 
works are performed to acclaim abroad but banned in his homeland 
has become a symbol of resistance to czechoslovakias communist 
authorities 
on tuesday havel was convicted of participating in a banned 
rally and sentenced to nine months in prison it was the latest 
government move against the countrys bestknown dissident since the 
1950s 
books with the lined face of the blond mustachioed writer are 
not found in czechoslovak libraries or bookshops but havels 
outspoken human rights statements have brought him admiration beyond 
his works 
what is encouraging is that the young people know him his 
brother ivan said in an interview this week at the prague flat the 
two share with their wives this is paradoxical whatever happens 
bad to him whatever happens good to him everything only increases 
his popularity 
when the 52yearold havel was invited on stage at a folk music 
festival in september 5000 people cheered 
when the authorities surprisingly allowed an independent 
demonstration in prague on dec 10 crowds chanted long live 
havel before he could speak 
about 100 sympathizers gave the same chant tuesday when havel was 
led to court and more than 2000 czechoslovak intellectuals 
including communist party members had signed petitions for havels 
release 
born oct 5 1936 the son of a civil engineer who built several 
famous prague landmarks he first encountered difficulties with 
authorities in the 1950s when his bourgeois background barred him 
from university studies 
between 1963 and 1968 in a flowering of czechoslovak culture 
that produced many wellknown films and writers havel had three 
plays performed in prague 
but after the sovietled invasion of 1968 havel was among dozens 
of writers whose works were banned in their homeland 
a critical open letter to communist leader gustav husak in 1975 
and his part in founding the charter 77 human rights movement in 
1977 led to almost constant harassment and detention 
in the letter to husak havel accused the communist authorities 
of creating a bureaucratic order of grey monotony that stifles all 
individuality 
true enough the country is calm havel wrote then calm as 
a morgue or as a grave wouldnt you say 
in 1979 when havel was convicted for sedition and sentenced to 
four years in prison nobody in czechoslovakia spoke up for him 
but he already was wellknown in the west where he received 
numerous awards and his plays drew critical praise 
in giving havel the erasmus prize in 1986 the rotterdambased 
erasmus foundation said he was driven by the search for truth in 
its purest form and lauded his ability to be critical of societies 
in both east and west 
havel has refused many invitations to go to the west fearing 
that would mean leaving behind his native prague and his wife of 24 
years olga last year a book of his letters from prison to olga 
havel was published in the west 
he would like to travel in eastern europe he told the associated 
press in an interview last year but i dont think they will give 
me a passport he added with a smile 
