<DOCNO> AP890221-0153 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the supreme court said tuesday it will consider 
relaxing significantly the socalled exclusionary rule that bars 
from criminal trials any evidence police seized unlawfully 
the court said it will use a case from chicago to decide whether 
statements made by a criminal defendant after an unlawful arrest may 
be used by prosecutors to contradict a defense witness trial 
testimony 
the court previously has allowed prosecutors to use unlawfully 
seized evidence to contradict a defendants own trial testimony but 
the justices never before have allowed the use of such evidence to 
rebut other witnesses testimony 
the illinois supreme court by a 43 vote allowed such evidence 
to be introduced at the trial of darryl james sentenced to 30 years 
in prison for a 1982 murder 
james was 15 when arrested in his mothers beauty parlor for two 
aug 30 1982 shootings he was tried as an adult 
prosecutors said james shot and killed geliria boyd and wounded 
another youth in a latenight confrontation on a south chicago 
street 
several prosecution witnesses identified james as the triggerman 
and testified that on the night of the crime he had long 
reddishbrown hair at his trial james had short black hair 
james did not testify at his trial but two defense witnesses 
testified in his behalf one said that james had short black hair 
the night of the shootings 
prosecutors then won court permission to let a police detective 
testify that james when arrested said he had long reddishbrown 
hair the night of the crime 
the trial judge previously had ruled that james arrest was 
unlawful because police at the time did not have a court warrant or 
probable cause to suspect him of committing a crime as a result 
the police detective was not allowed to testify directly about what 
james had told him the night of the arrest 
but the detective was allowed to testify about james remarks to 
rebut the defense witness testimony 
in a related case from michigan the court said it will decide 
whether evidence obtained unlawfully after a defendant has been 
arraigned can ever be used in court 
a michigan appeals court said no and threw out tyris lemont 
harveys 1986 conviction in detroit on charges of criminal sexual 
conduct he had been sentenced to six to 10 years in prison 
the state court said harvey was entitled to a new trial because a 
police officer should not have been allowed to testify about 
comments harvey made during an unlawful police interrogation six 
days before his trial 
the testimony was not offered as part of the prosecutions case 
but only to rebut some of harveys trial testimony 
the state court acknowledged that evidence obtained in violation 
of a defendants fourth or fifth amendment rights to be free from 
unreasonable police searches and the privilege against 
selfincrimination sometimes may be used to rebut or impeach a 
defendants testimony 
but it ruled that the statement made to the police officer 
violated harveys sixth amendment right to effective legal help 
a statement so acquired may not be used for any purpose 
including impeachment the state court ruled 
the ruling was appealed by wayne county prosecutors 
the cases are james vs illinois 886075 and michigan vs 
harvey 88512 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
