<TEXT>
computerequipped citizens can fire 
off an angry electronic letter to city hall see if their favorite 
book is at the library or check the bus schedule in a pioneering 
program switched on tuesday 
experts say santa monicas public electronic network is at the 
leading edge of a national trend linking local governments to their 
constituents through computers 
this affluent coastal los angeles suburb began enrolling computer 
owners in the service tuesday and city manager john jalili said 
interest appeared high though a customer count for the free service 
wasnt immediately available 
once a citizen has been enrolled and assigned a password to get 
into the system he or she will be able to tap into city files on 
proposed developments and other city council action find out how to 
get city permits and licenses get schedules for city services and 
get a range of consumer advice 
theyll also be able to sound off directing electronic mail 
at council members department heads and the public at large 
the city promises to respond 
i love it said michael hill a teacher and active citizen 
who was the first to sign up for pen we live in an electronic age 
and we have this technology that allows us to use computers to 
access information 
he planned to fire up his home computer tuesday afternoon to 
offer some ideas on how to fit a park improvement project into the 
new budget 
then ill probably email electronic mail the information 
services department head and congratulate him on a job well done 
hill said 
the system is housed in a computer separate from the citys 
internal data processing to head off the threat of hackers 
seeking inside information or planting destructive viruses 
although santa monicas system appears to go further than most 
many local governments around the country are experimenting with 
computer citizen communications said ted shogry of public 
technology inc a washington dc group that researches 
technology for local governemnts 
kansas city mo and hillsborough county fla have 24hour 
city halls which allow citizens to browse through reams of 
information using computer kiosks set up in public places he said 
the organization is planning a 12city test later this year of a 
videotext information system linking citizens with their 
governments the cities have yet to be chosen 
charlotte nc and fort worth texas have voice mail 
systems for callers to get recorded information on a variety of 
services and problems he said 
its attracting a lot of interest by local governments across 
the country shogry said theres a growing awareness of how 
telecommunications and computer technology can be used to involve 
more people 
santa monicas jalili sees the system as a way to improve service 
to citizens 
first of all its going to stop the phone game where people 
are transferred to eight different places jalili said and 
there are people who during their work day cant call in and when 
they get home city hall is closed 
of course many people who need help or information from city 
hall dont have personal computers 
in santa monica known for the liberal politics of such celebrity 
residents as actress jane fonda project organizers are sensitive to 
the perception theyre bypassing the poor 
terminals have been installed in all libraries and there are 
plans to put them in recreation buildings and in a senior citizens 
center under construction 
elsewhere the equipment put in public places is designed for 
easy use by those who arent familiar with computers some have 
touchsensitive screens to make typing unnecessary and all have 
simple instructions to lead users throught the microchip maze 
my personal opinion is that for the electronic democracy to 
become a reality the needs of the poor or less educated will have 
to be kind of aggressively addressed shogry said 
in the case of santa monica a survey found 33 percent of 
residents owned personal computers and 23 percent had modems the 
devices needed to allow the computers to communicate over telephone 
lines 
for now the experiment is free to the city and to subscribers 
the 350000 system was a gift from two computer companies hewlett 
packard co donated the machines and metasystems inc provided the 
software 
but fees arent ruled out in the future said jalili depending 
on how much staff time is involved 
