senate democratic leaders said tuesday that 
congress will review a law governing the use of national security 
secrets in criminal cases because of the legal tangle created by the 
trial of oliver north 
senate majority leader george mitchell dmaine said the use of 
an independent counsel to prosecute north on charges of lying to 
congress about the irancontra affair had not been anticipated in 
the law covering how to handle secret evidence 
in this case the balance which the law assumed would be there 
does not exist mitchell told reporters it is obvious that the 
prior administration and this administration is not eagerly seeking 
prosecution indeed its political interest lies in no trial at 
all 
to help ensure that the administration did not forfeit the north 
case for political reasons the senate intelligence committee held a 
closeddoor session to hear from cia director william webster on the 
administrations reasons for dropping conspiracy charges against 
north in january norths trial on 12 other charges began tuesday 
we heard from members of the intelligence community who shared 
their national security concerns about information that could be 
developed during the course of the trial now under way said sen 
david boren dokla chairman of the intelligence panel 
boren declined to say whether he was satisfied that those 
concerns were legitimate or to characterize websters level of worry 
about the classified information saying he did not want to open 
himself to charges of influencing the case 
congress passed the classified information procedures act in 
1980 propelled by a spate of cases in which defendants threatened 
to disclose government secrets as part of their defense against 
criminal charges 
the law defines national security secrets and allows a trial 
judge to screen such information before a trial to determine whether 
the material can be used in open court the judge can dismiss a case 
or specific counts of an indictment if the government objects to 
disclosure of classified information 
the same law requires the justice department to report to 
congress on cases not prosecuted or charges dropped because of fears 
of disclosure of secrets 
we will carefully review the law when this is over to see if 
changes are necessary mitchell said 
we are dealing with situations here which might not have been 
anticipated by the law when it was written added boren it 
would be appropriate for us to reflect upon when all is said and 
done in the north case 
