<TEXT>
the bush administration on tuesday targeted 
south korea and the 12nation european community for possible trade 
sanctions if the countries do not agree to lower trade barriers 
blocking us export sales of telecommunications equipment 
the decision was announced by us trade representative carla 
hills who acted after a fivemonth investigation required under the 
1988 trade act 
the law requires the united states to open negotiations with 
countries deemed by us trade officials to be blocking sales by 
american firms of telecommunications equipment 
if the talks dont succeed in removing trade barriers within a 
year the law requires the administration to impose trade sanctions 
however the administration has the option of extending the talks 
for as long as two more years if us officials believe that 
progress is being made 
the announcement said the decision was made by mrs hills after 
reviewing comments from industry labor other federal agencies 
members of congress and foreign governments 
criteria for the examination included not only trade barriers 
but also each nations market potential and any measurable progress 
that it might be making toward trade liberalization the trade 
office said in a statement 
