<TEXT>
soviet military forces left 10 million to 30 
million land mines behind them when they pulled out of afghanistan 
posing a tremendous impediment to the safe return and 
resettlement of millions of refugees a defense department official 
told congress on wednesday 
the official edward w gnehm jr deputy assistant secretary of 
defense for near eastern affairs said the pentagon operating under 
united nations auspices has begun a comprehensive program of mine 
awareness and disposal training for afghan refugees in camps inside 
pakistan 
a state department witness reported meanwhile the soviets have 
halted air strikes into afghanistan from bases inside soviet 
territory ending the largest remaining problem of active warfare in 
the country 
howard schaffer deputy assistant secretary of state for near 
eastern affairs said also that because the level of human need 
inside the country is enormous the bush administration is 
taking a fresh sympathetic look into the possibility of 
extending humanitarian assistance 
he also said without offering an explanation the state 
department is confident that whatever government emerges in kabul in 
the aftermath of the withdrawal of soviet troops from afghanistan 
will be neither communist nor messianic islamic 
testifying before the house foreign affairs subcommittee on asian 
and pacific affairs gnehm said a 40person military training team 
part of a project dubbed operation safe passage has been 
dispatched to pakistan and will spend six months increasing the 
awareness of large numbers of afghan refugees of the threats they 
will face as they return to their homes 
he said afghan teams will be trained and given special equipment 
to neutralize and dispose of land mines in their country 
gnehm said that training posters have been produced in some of 
the principal languages of afghanistan which warn thousands of 
people have been martyred by mines dont touch mines they are 
deadly and all kinds of mines have been placed in afghanistan 
gnehm called the training program an unprecedented application 
of special military skills for alleviating suffering from the 
aftermaths of a terrible and brutal war 
estimates of the number of mines range from 10 million to 30 
million gnehm said most of the mines are antipersonnel devices 
that have been scattered almost indiscriminately 
responding to questions he said that while the soviets have said 
they would they were defusing mines and were giving the communist 
government in kabul maps showing their location to our knowledge 
neither of these things has happened 
he said the locations of the mines would be extremely difficult 
to map since many of the antipersonnel devices were sewn from planes 
and helicopters 
he said an another danger is posed by the fact that heavy rains 
have washed some of the explosive devices down from hill and 
mountainsides into valleys used for farming 
gnehm also reported that since the first flight of an air force 
c5 cargo plane to pakistan in march 1986 there have been a total 
of 76 relief flights carrying more than 47 million pounds of excess 
defense department property and privately donated supplies all 
intended to aid the refugees 
additionally he said some 680 injured afghan citizens have been 
flown to western europe egypt and the united states to receive 
medical treatment 
