<TEXT>
a retired judge tuesday recommended a 30 million 
increase in his 852 million judgment against amoco corp for 
oilspill damage from the 1978 wreck of a supertanker off the french 
coast 
the revised award would be shared by the government of france 
which would receive the single largest portion 444 million and 
some 100 french towns affected by the spill that fouled 100 miles of 
coastline 
frank mcgarr who retired as a us district court judge after 
his 1988 ruling continues to serve as special master in the case 
and made the recommendation after being asked by parties in the case 
to reconsider the award 
the recommendation is subject to approval by another federal 
judge no date has been set for a final judgment 
both sides objected to the revised award as well and vowed to 
appeal none of the money has been paid the towns had received 73 
million in the original judgment and sought an additional 8 million 
but received only 200000 more 
todays damage determinations continue to support the position 
the amoco parties have maintained throughout that the claims of 
damage from this unfortunate incident were exaggerated 
chicagobased amoco said in a statement 
what we will be asking the appeals court to do is recognize the 
damage to the environment the livelihoods of the people in 
brittany and the quality of life said attorney barry kingham 
who represented the towns association of oystermen and fishermen 
hoteliers and the two french counties most affected by the spill 
the judge refused to recognize those damages and he continues 
to reject them he simply gave outofpocket expenses for the 
cleanup effort 
attorneys for both sides said the revised award totals about 115 
million 61 million in damages and between 54 million and 60 
million in interest 
the supertanker amoco cadiz ran aground two miles off the 
brittany coast the tanker which had lost the use of its rudder 
had been under tow through the english channel when the towlines 
snapped in hurricaneforce winds and heavy seas 
the tanker lost 68 million gallons of mostly iranian light crude 
oil valued at 24 million the spill killed thousands of birds and 
millions of sea creatures and washing wave after wave of thick black 
tar along the coast 
in 1984 mcgarr ruled that amoco and two subsidiaries were liable 
because of negligence in the design repair and maintenance of the 
vessel which was 300 feet wide and longer than three football 
fields 
