<TEXT>
the energy departments master plan for 
refurbishing its nuclear weapons plants puts too little emphasis on 
environmental cleanup at the decrepit facilities a general 
accounting office official told a house panel tuesday 
j dexter peach the gaos assistant comptroller general also 
raised questions about the departments proposal for building two 
new nuclear reactors to produce tritium a perishable gas used in 
the manufacture of nuclear warheads 
the agency the investigative arm of congress has prepared more 
than 50 reports on pollution and operational problems in the weapons 
industry since 1981 and has been critical of the energy departments 
past management of arms plants 
peach told a house armed services subcommittee that the energy 
departments plan if carried out would revitalize the nations 
nuclear weapons complex by the year 2010 but would leave key 
environmental problems unsolved the plan envisions spending at 
least 244 billion over the next 21 years with 32 billion is 
earmarked for cleaning up environmental damage 
in our opinion the plan does not adequately address the 
cleanup of existing facilities and decontamination of facilities as 
they are retired from service peach said 
the energy department plan was endorsed by former president 
reagan shortly before he left office president bush has not said 
whether he supports it 
james d watkins bushs designated energy secretary has not 
commented publicly on the modernization report but he was almost 
certain to face intense questioning about it at his senate 
confirmation hearing wednesday 
peach in his testimony said congress should closely review the 
energy departments announced plans to build two new reactors to 
produce tritium the departments only existing tritiumproducing 
reactors are shut down because of safety and technical faults and 
they are expected to be permanently retired in the 1990s 
the energy department wants to spend 68 billion to build the 
two new reactors some critics have questioned the need for both 
reactors in view of the possibility that future ussoviet arms 
control deals could reduce the need for tritium 
troy e wade ii the departments acting assistant secretary for 
defense programs told the house panel the high cost of building the 
new reactors was justified 
it is an issue of capacity to assure the necessary supplies 
over the next two decades he said adding that it would be 
prudent to have new reactors based on two different technologies in 
order to guard against possible failures 
peach criticized the energy department master plan for failing to 
spell out how and over what time period the environmental damage 
caused by nuclear weapons production such as contaminated soil and 
groundwater could be cleaned up 
uncertainty still exists not only regarding the size of the 
problems but also regarding the extent to which doe sites can be 
cleaned up some locations may be irreversibly contaminated peach 
said 
peach said the master plan calls for spending 401 million in the 
coming budget year on environmental cleanup that eventually will 
cost up to 70 billion 
several members of the house panel including john spratt 
dsc also criticized the energy department saying it has put 
more emphasis on nuclear materials production than on safe and 
environmentally sound operations 
ray berube the departments deputy assistant secretary for 
environment said there is no current immediate public health and 
safety risk posed by the weapons plants he said there would be a 
threat if the environmental issues were put off 
wade meanwhile said the department still expected to restart at 
least one of its tritiumproducing reactors at the savannah river 
plant in south carolina by the end of the year he said a firm 
timetable would be available next month 
