to stop him 
paul wade price who is serving the third year of a 10year 
prison sentence after he pleaded guilty to one count of child 
molestation said in the videotaped testimony he molested at least 
25 students over the 14 years he taught at the cherokee elementary 
school in western north carolina 
price said his victims were primarily boys aged 8 through 12 
one that was the age group i was teaching and secondly im 
sure that there was the possibility that younger children dont 
generally tell things as the older children do he said under 
questioning by ken ballen chief counsel to a special investigative 
unit of the senate select committee on indian affairs 
price has been a prisoner at the butner federal correctional 
institution in butner nc since 1986 
the testimony came in the third week of hearings by the 
committee which has been looking into various alleged misdeeds on 
indian reservations within the bia and among other agencies that do 
business with indians 
after hearing testimony on contracting irregularities and 
organized crime involvement in indian gaming operations the 
committee is now concentrating on the problem of child sex abuse on 
reservations 
price told ballen he was surprised that he could continue his 
activity on and off for 14 years 
this is strictly hindsight price said looking back it 
certainly is a phenomenon that is hard to understand 
in 1974 as a provision for receiving federal aid congress 
required the states to enact laws mandating that individuals who 
suspect sexual abuse in a school report it to the authorities but 
there is no such federal law and state statutes do not apply to 
indian reservations and bia schools 
two teachers testified that they knew or heard rumors of prices 
activities but despite complaints to school authorities nothing 
was done until the fbi began its investigation in 1985 following a 
mothers complaint 
the mother keneithea haigler said that when she told the school 
superintendent that her 8yearold son had been molested by price 
they let me know that they knew what this teacher was doing and 
they were just waiting for some mother to come in and do something 
about it 
another mother patricia tramper said price threatened the boys 
if they discussed the matter with their parents 
price who was unemotional during his taped interview said at 
its close that he believes he always wanted to get caught because he 
could not stop himself from his activities 
ive had time of course in prison to reflect over this and te 
seriousness of it he said 
fondling is you know in my mind i was thinking it really 
doesnt hurt anybody but i know now how much it does hurt he 
said 
we just must find a way to help the children first and of 
course the molesters also above all the children who really 
dont know what theyre getting into he said telling the panel 
that he himself had been molested at the age of 8 
later witnesses from the bia said that despite a new policy 
requiring school personnel to report cases of sex abuse the bia 
does not get much information william mehojah bia branch chief for 
indian elementary and secondary school programs said no 
disciplinary action has ever been taken for failure to report 
mehojah and the others advocated enactment of a federal law 
similar to those in the states making failure to report alleged sex 
abuse a crime the opinion was echoed by two fbi agents who 
investigate crime on indian reservations in arizona and the dakotas 
and law enforcement officials working for the bia and local 
authorities 
fbi agent david small said interviews with pedophiles have 
indicated that child molesters gravitate to indian reservations 
because there is little supervision and they usually are in remote 
areas making it easy to prey on children 
robert haley general chairman of the indian law enforcement 
section of the international association of chiefs of police said 
investigation of child abuse cases are sometimes hampered by tribes 
which refuse to let the children off the reservation to testify 
mehojah said many teachers have gone to work before background 
checks were complete because of paperwork delays 
