<TEXT>
the president of the american federation 
of teachers says that unions havent been quick enough in keeping up 
with changes in the workforce 
and albert shanker espouses unorthodox methods of restoring the 
stature of unions in the workplace including the schools where his 
members teach 
among his proposed changes in the education system are abolishing 
the department of education and placing its duties in the labor 
department firing incompetent teachers and transforming high 
schools into campuslike environments where students have some 
flexibility in choosing classes 
in this country we go on the pendulum swing system shanker 
said tuesday during a breakfast meeting with reporters covering the 
aflcio executive council meeting here first we had tough schools 
with rigorous standards where most kids are pushed out then we move 
to soft schools where everybody graduates but very few learn 
anything 
now we go back to the other way shanker said its pretty 
clear that if you have two ways of doing things and neither is 
working its time to find a third way 
that third way in shankers view might include ideas unions 
have traditionally opposed including the use of parttime teachers 
a shortage of qualified math and science teachers has made the use 
of parttimers a viable approach that labor should support although 
those teachers are unlikely to join the union shanker said 
we have to encourage nontraditional methods said shanker 
who has been president of the 690000member aft since 1974 
he carries that approach over to overall union organizing a 
oncemilitant union leader calling on his colleagues to relax the 
standards he says are partly to blame for the declining share of 
unionized workers in the united states 
unions themselves have not adequately recongnized the changing 
of the labor force shanker said its the failure in many cases 
to switch the nature of your appeal fast enough 
as the demographics of the workforce change to include fewer 
workers in highrisk factory jobs and more in whitecollar 
professions unions must change equally fast to appeal to 
professionals shanker said 
included in those changes he said should be new membership 
categories such as associate memberships that would offer workers 
who are not members of a collective bargaining unit some union 
services 
that concept is the subject of a heated internal debate that 
delayed the scheduled release this week of a major report on labor 
organizing hardliners object to the concept of associate 
memberships on grounds that labor is conceding too much in its drive 
to fill up membership rolls 
