the group seeks information on more than 150 prisoners mostly 
from the 900000strong ethnic turkish minority which makes up about 
10 percent of the population said the report 
since 1984 the bulgarian government has denied that a turkish 
minority exists in the country it also says there are no human 
rights abuses 
ahmed hasanov aptullov a 29yearold philosophy lecturer from 
sofia university and three others were arrested after producing 
leaflets in 1986 rallying turks to oppose the assimilation amnesty 
international said 
they were imprisoned for eight to 10 years each amnesty 
international considers them prisoners of conscience the human 
rights groups term for people who use nonviolent means to express 
themselves 
the report described in detail the cases of 11 prisoners of 
conscience and said amnesty international seeks information on 
another 144 prisoners 
the group said another prisoner of conscience ismail mehmedov 
hyuseinov was arrested in 1985 for refusing to accept his new name 
and applying to emigrate to turkey 
he was badly beaten in prison but released to internal exile 
after losing 88 pounds on a hunger strike the government said he 
was freed in 1987 but amnesty international said it has been told 
he remains in exile in northwest bulgaria 
other prisoners have been tortured by prolonged beating on the 
soles of the feet the report said 
amnesty international said it has long been concerned about 
prisoners of conscience in bulgaria and welcomed the recent 
dialogue begun with the bulgarian government 
it said bulgarian authorities supplied information in 1987 after 
repeated requests by amnesty international the group met with some 
officials including a newly formed committee on human rights in 
1988 
the report said concerns remain and reliable information has been 
scarce because of censorship and contradictory official statements 
name changes have made identification difficult 
</TEXT>
