<TEXT>
joe clark the principal of eastside high school in paterson 
nj decided that a baseball bat was as good an educational tool as 
books his controversial tactics are the focus of the new warner 
bros film lean on me the movie is reviewed this week by 
education writer lee mitgang who has covered the clark controversy 
and film critic bob thomas in sidebyside reviews 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
anyone who has ever met joe clark the principal of eastside high 
school in paterson nj knows that he would never allow a film 
crew into his school unless for the greater glory of joe clark 
this is after all the same joe clark who in 1987 virtually 
barred a state monitoring team from inspecting his building 
so its hardly a surprise that lean on me a new warner bros 
film shot on location at eastside and purporting to be based on the 
true story of the tough principal turns out to be little more 
than blackboard jungle propaganda aimed at vindicating clarks 
batandbullhorn educational methods 
warner bros has sunk a long way since last april when it made 
its commendable foray into the school world with the vastly superior 
stand and deliver a film with twice the plot and a hundred 
times more character development than this latest stand and 
deliver was about a high school math teacher in a los angeles 
barrio school who proved that inner city kids respond to the same 
kinds of positive things that rich kids do adults who really care 
clark by contrast captured headlines in recent years as the 
principal who restored order to an innercity school described by 
local prosecutors as a cauldron of violence 
in the seven years clark has run eastside he has indeed tamed 
this once graffitiscarred school 
his methods shocked some but pleased many others including 
thenus secretary william j bennett whose frequent praise helped 
make clark a national celebrity he prowled the hallways with a 
baseball bat and bullhorn suspended hundreds of students and made 
it clear to all that the sign in his office one way my way 
applied to teachers and students alike 
lean on me paints clark as a principal who bleeds for his 
kids but will stop at nothing including breaking labor and fire 
laws cursing out his superiors and humiliating teachers to 
achieve his aims 
clark won headlines as a black educator who blamed his schools 
problems on a failed social welfare system 
hardly have the opening credits finished rolling before the film 
has made sure no one has missed any of these points 
it opens with a brief shot of eastside high in more idyllic days 
in 1967 the school was mostly white boys wore ties clark then a 
young teacher wore a dashiki 
twenty years later we see a very different eastside with 
graffiti covering anything standing still long enough to be 
spraypainted girls openly molested drugs freely dispensed fights 
commonplace 
into the breach steps clark his challenge brush aside the 
smallminded politicians and school board restore order and raise 
standardized test scores quickly enough to avoid a state takeover of 
the school 
hey no sweat 
morgan freeman turns in a credible performance as clark 
capturing nicely clarks selfrighteousness the script by michael 
schiffer doesnt leave much room for character development but that 
wasnt the point of this film anyway clark himself had this to say 
of freeman as filming proceeded last june hes a good actor but i 
dont think anybody can fully portray me theres only one joe 
clark 
how true 
by lee mitgang ap education writer 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
if any critics organization offered an award for the most 
manipulative director the lifetime achievement award would surely 
go to john g avildsen consider his ability to rouse audiences to 
anger revulsion and especially the overwhelming joy of victory 
over impossible odds in such films as joe save the tiger 
rocky neighbors and the karate kid 
the new warner bros release lean on me is quintessential 
avildsen from the very first frame he grabs the viewers and plays 
their emotions with the skill of a disc jockey at a disco turntable 
you cheer and weep tears of joy despite the realization that you are 
being shamelessly used 
the film is based on the headlinemaking career of joe clark the 
black educator who turned the paterson nj eastside high school 
from a ghetto jungle into a model of achievement wielding a 
symbolic baseball bat michael schiffers script obviously takes 
liberties with the facts since it is orchestrated in a series of 
audiencestirring sequences 
joe clark morgan freeman is a zealous teacher whose fierce 
temper and outspokenness has relegated him to being principal of a 
white grammar school when eastside high is threatened with a 
takeover by the state because of a dismal academic record the mayor 
alan north and school superintendent robert guillaume 
reluctantly enlist clark as eastside principal 
clark begins by ousting all the drug dealers and goofoffs 
painting over the graffiti and haranguing both students and 
teachers he goes overboard alienating his staff and making an 
enemy of a powerhungry activist lynne thigpen clark is jailed 
for locking the school doors to keep out drug dealers but you can 
guess who triumphs in the end 
schiffer who also wrote the slambang colors has provided a 
messy screenplay overloaded with shouted speeches and offering an 
improbably sentimental climax that would make frank capra seem like 
chekhov but for those willing to leave cynicism at home lean on 
me can be a moving experience thanks in large part to morgan 
freemans powerful presence he is a marvel of raw energy commanding 
force 
beverly tyler has the relatively thankless role of clarks 
longsuffering assistant but she performs admirably the students 
are uniformly great 
norman twain produced the film which is rated pg13 mostly for 
language and violent action refreshingly the film makes little use 
of expletives which might have abounded in such a film running 
time 104 minutes 
by bob thomas associated press writer 
</TEXT>
