<TEXT>
karl fuls was angry and frustrated after losing 
his legs to circulatory problems what i needed was to talk to me 
now he says 
therapists counselors doctors social workers nobody helped 
me how much money i could have saved how many dead ends i could 
have avoided 
savvier now and far more selfsufficient fuls last august set up 
the broken wing a nonprofit organization that matches the newly 
disabled with a person of the same sex age background and handicap 
to discuss strategies for coping 
everybodys got questions fuls 62 said sitting in a 
motorized chair at the rehabilitation institute of pittsburgh during 
a recent meeting three of the 16 people were in wheelchairs three 
had canes and several wore leg braces 
theyre not going to ask a doctor theyre not going to ask a 
therapist they will ask questions to people like themselves how do 
you put makeup on how do you take a shower is my sex life over 
things like this he said 
its all new i cry being with somebody like you helps you 
can even laugh said mary ann tomko a 50yearold grocery 
employee who sought moral support and practical advice from 
broken wing members after her right leg was amputated abovethe knee 
last fall because of a blood clot 
her parents with whom she lives accompany their only child to 
meetings 
it affects me too i thought i was going to die eleanor 
tomko 71 said her eyes filling with tears 
john mccrorey 57 whose left side has been paralyzed for eight 
years because of a stroke thrives on helping others the former 
engineer regularly chats with an advertising executive whos 
recovering from a stroke its just good to talk about our mutual 
problems its like losing half of your body and dragging it along 
with you your body commits suicide 
its good to have hope theres light at the end of the 
tunnel 
occupational therapist annie miller the broken wings secretary 
acknowledges there are innumerable support groups to which the 
handicapped can turn but they operate on a communication or 
verbal level 
they get together they meet they discuss and emotionally they 
may feel better about their disabilities 
the broken wing offers more than just emotional support and 
conversation we are out there to provide a service to physically 
make people more independent miller said 
fuls had no idea how much hed learned about coping most of it 
the hard way until 1984 when he was leafing through his diary 
he began writing about his health problems a year before being 
diagnosed with arteriosclerosis after his fourth and final 
amputation in 1982 for example his wheelchair rolled backward down 
a ramp outside his house only later did he learn he needed a 
special chair for amputees that accounts for the imbalance 
i was mad he said it made me start thinking 
soon afterward the idea for a network to nurture independence 
was born 
after several years of research and planning the broken wing 
finally was chartered last august with headquarters at fuls home in 
suburban white oak 
forty strong and growing the broken wing is seeking grants for 
office space and a computer system that would link the longtime 
disabled to the newly handicapped eventually nationwide since late 
january fuls has been talking to support groups in search of 
volunteers 
his message is simple do they remember how hard it was for 
them to adjust to a handicapped lifestyle and would they be willing 
to have someone else benefit from their experience 
