<TEXT>
the supreme court today rejected a prominent 
stock brokers challenge to the power of the securities and exchange 
commission to crack down on fraud 
the court without comment left intact rulings that meyer 
blinder and the brokerage firm he founded blinder robinson amp co 
say unfairly restrict their business activities 
the case stems from a civil sec enforcement action in 1980 
against blinder and his firm 
blinder began the business in westbury long island ny and 
moved its headquarters to denver in the late 1970s it became one of 
the nations leading underwriters of penny stocks or lowpriced 
securities 
the commission accused blinder and the firm of deceiving 
investors in underwriting a 25 million sale of stock in american 
leisure corp the stock sale was intended to finance construction 
and operation of a casino hotel in atlantic city nj 
us district judge richard p matsch in denver ruled in 1982 the 
firm defrauded investors by withholding important information 
including the real risks of the casino venture 
the judge said the firms sales force practiced a program of 
deliberately deceptive misinformation which meyer blinder 
orchestrated 
matsch issued an injunction permanently barring blinder and his 
firm from engaging in similar practices 
blinder went back to court in 1986 to have the injunction lifted 
he said he and the firm are rehabilitated noting that he had 
replaced his sales force since 1982 and had given millions of 
dollars to charity 
he also said the injunction was having dire unforeseen 
consequences on his business he said about a dozen states have 
taken steps to limit or ban blinder robinson from selling 
securities and the sec has imposed sanctions based on the court 
order 
blinder challenged the constitutionality of the secs enforcement 
powers in such cases blinder said it violates the separation of 
powers to permit the commission to enforce the laws because the sec 
is only partly accountable to the president 
commission members are appointed by the president with the 
consent of the senate and may be removed from office by the 
president for inefficiency neglect of duty or misconduct 
the 10th us circuit court of appeals last august refused to 
lift the injunction against the stock brokerage or its founder 
the appeals court rejected arguments that evidence of 
rehabilitation means the injunction no longer is needed to protect 
the public the appeals court also ruled that the secs powers do 
not violate the constitution 
the case is blinder robinson vs sec 88850 
</TEXT>
