the stock then lost nearly 20 percent of its value by noon 
falling from its friday closing price of 550 to 450 a share the 
stock made up a little ground in the afternoon closing at 475 
melanie hale a utility analyst with mccarthy crisanti maffei 
inc of new york said the article in the new issue of barrons 
apparently prompted the fall public service spokesman nicholas 
ashooh said company officials had no other explanation 
headlined common mistake a bankrupt utility generates more 
speculative heat than light the article was written by william 
fry president of progressive united corp and general partner in 
meridian strategic investments lp two indianapolis firms that 
invest primarily in companies under bankruptcy protection 
fry noted that public services common stock price has more than 
doubled in the 13 months since it became the first major 
investorowned utility to seek bankruptcy protection since the great 
depression debt from its 36 percent share of the stalled seabrook 
nuclear power project forced public service to seek bankruptcy 
refuge 
in large measure the rise in the shares reflects investors 
faith that psnh and its common stock will revive when the 
company finally emerges from chapter 11 fry wrote 
but at least for common stockholders that faith isnt likely 
to be rewarded fry wrote 
quite the contrary holders of the companys common 
stockholders could find themselves with totally worthless paper 
when psnh comes out of chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy code 
that is because public services liabilities exceed the market 
value of its assets fry explained and under bankruptcy law 
bondholders and other senior claims must be paid in full before 
lesser claims may receive any compensation 
public service has secured and unsecured obligations of nearly 
2 billion it also has nearly 500 million of liquidating value of 
preferred stock which takes priority in a reorganization against 
the obligations the company has a conventional utility plant with a 
book value of about 650 million and its investment in seabrook 
fry wrote 
he noted that it remains uncertain whether seabrook ever will be 
allowed to operate commercially and even if it does public service 
is unlikely to recover what it has invested in the reactor 
even an acquisition offer by northeast utilities of connecticut 
estimated to be worth 2 billion if seabrook operates would leave 
nothing for preferred stockholders much less common stockholders 
fry said 
its extremely speculative to think that common shareholders 
will get anything at all in a reorganization fry concluded so 
if you have an uncontrollable urge to speculate in psnh its bonds 
appear to be a much more rational vehicle 
