<TEXT>
polaroid corp began a 11 billion stock 
buyback tuesday and said the plan may include 325 million in 
privately negotiated share purchases a move some analysts said was 
aimed at the companys hostile suitor 
the instant camera maker which announced jan 30 that it would 
undertake the buyback began a cash tender offer for 16 million 
shares at 50 a share in addition polaroid said it would 
repurchase 325 million of its stock on the open market or in 
privately negotiated purchases 
the offer of private negotiations was seen by some as an 
invitation to shamrock holdings inc of burbank calif which holds 
a 67 percent stake in polaroid and is pursuing a 32 billion 
hostile takeover of the company 
theyre leaving the door wide open for greenmail said alex 
henderson an analyst with prudentialbache securities in new york 
i cant think of any other privately held block of stock other 
than shamrocks that would be negotiated individually 
greenmail is the practice of buying back shares held by a 
corporate raider at a premium compared with the market price in 
order to thwart a potential or actual hostile bid critics say the 
practice favors raiders at the expense of other stockholders 
but some wall street analysts said polaroid seemed to be making 
an effort to placate its stockholders by offering a premium for some 
of their shares 
polaroids buyback offer of 50 a share is 5 over shamrocks 
last bid and 625 above fridays closing price for polaroid shares 
on the new york stock exchange 
on tuesday polaroid stock fell 37 cents to close at 4337 a 
share 
charles k ryan an analyst for merrill lynch capital markets 
said the drop reflected anxiety about the possibility of greenmail 
polaroids announcement is good for 30 percent of the stock and 
bad for 70 percent ryan said it does provide shareholder value 
for some of the shares but if they remove shamrock by doing this 
the remaining shares could decline in value 
shamrock called the buyback a further attempt at entrenchment by 
polaroids management 
we believe that polaroids partial buyback is a far leass 
attractive alternative than shamrocks 45 cash offer for all 
polaroid shares shamrock president stanley p gold said in a 
statement 
shamrock a television and radio concern owned by the roy e 
disney family owns about 48 million shares of polaroid and is 
waging a proxy fight for control of the board of directors at the 
may 9 annual meeting in addition to its hostile tender offer 
polaroid has been resisting shamrock since the california company 
made a friendly but unsolicited offer of 40 a share last july in 
september shamrock launched a hostile offer of 42 per share last 
month it boosted that offer to 45 
polaroid last july put 97 million shares into an employee stock 
ownership plan in january the company announced a recapitalization 
plan that included selling 300 million of preferred stock to 
corporate partners lp a private investment group 
shamrock has filed suit in delaware chancery court in an effort 
to block polaroids buyback the esop and the sale of stock to 
corporate partners polaroid is incorporated in delaware 
polaroid said its stock repurchase offer expires march 20 and is 
subject to various conditions including definitive financing an 
absence of adverse decisions in lawsuits with shamrock and changes 
in shamrocks hostile bid if more than 16 million shares are 
tendered polaroid said it will buy shares back on a pro rata basis 
